The title is pretty self-explanatory. The HTML responsible looks like this:

{code}
#!HTML

<a href="http://www.python.org/">Python 2.7.3 </a>
{code}

And it should like this:

{code}
#!HTML

<a href="http://www.python.org/">Python 2.7.3</a>
{code}

When I create a new repository, you conveniently provide the following shell commands to initialize with my own existing local version:

{code}
#!bash

$ cd /path/to/my/repo
$ git remote add origin https://myname@bitbucket.org/myname/myrepo.git
$ git push -u origin --all   # to push changes for the first time
{code}

While this is absolutely great, it would be even more so if I didn&#x27;t have to remove the dollar signs in front of them each time I copy the last two lines!

Kind regards,\\
Jesse the Game

When pushing to Bitbucket, some users may receive the following message:

{code}
#!bash

error: The requested URL returned error: 412 while accessing https://sh45park@bitbucket.org/sh45park/android-news-player.git/info/refs
fatal: HTTP request failed
{code}

This error message is erroneous and actually should inform the user that they don&#x27;t have a password set on their account.
